data.content:
## Thread.Abort Migration → .NET 8

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has **four** patterns that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| Cancellable work loop | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| ThreadAbortException as control flow | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| Thread.ResetAbort | `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| Blocking call interruption | `GetNextItem()` may block | Pass token to unblock |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. The entire preemptive abort model is gone — you **must** switch to cooperative cancellation where your code voluntarily checks for and responds to cancellation requests.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. We decide whether to continue
                // by checking the token in the while condition.
                // Since cancellation was requested, the loop exits naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for graceful shutdown
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

**`_running` → `CancellationToken`** — The volatile bool is replaced by `CancellationTokenSource`/`CancellationToken`, which is the standard .NET cancellation primitive. It integrates with async APIs, `WaitHandle`, and the BCL.

**`Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()`** — Instead of the runtime forcibly injecting an exception, you signal cancellation and the code responds at the next checkpoint.

**`catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)`** — The `when` guard ensures you only catch cancellation you initiated, not unrelated `OperationCanceledException` from other sources.

**`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — Not needed. After catching `OperationCanceledException`, the thread stays alive. The `while` loop condition checks the token and exits naturally.

**`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(2s)`** — `Join` actually waits for the thread to finish rather than blindly sleeping and hoping.

**`IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks.

---

### Critical: You Must Update `GetNextItem`

The blocking call is the hardest part. If `GetNextItem()` blocks indefinitely, cancellation stalls there because **cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints**. You must pass the token through:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks forever, unresponsive to cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER — wakes up when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` does synchronous I/O (e.g., `socket.Receive`), replace it with an async overload or use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(timeout)` in a polling loop.

---

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---------|--------|
| **Not passing token to `GetNextItem`** | Thread hangs forever on `Stop()` — cancellation never reaches the blocking call |
| **Not passing token through the full call chain** | `ProcessItem` may also do blocking work; it needs the token too |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it** | Let it propagate everywhere except this top-level loop |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks |
| **Assuming cancellation is immediate** | It only fires at the next `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or token-aware API call. Add checkpoints inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running |
